=== Departure from Lae ===

On <time datetime="1937-07-02T00:00Z">July 2, 1937, midnight [[GMT]]</time>, Earhart and Noonan took off from [[Lae Airfield]] ({{Coord|06|43|59|S|146|59|45|E|type:airport}}<ref>[http://gc.kls2.com/airport/AYLA.OLD Lae Airfield (AYLA)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018133354/http://gc.kls2.com/airport/AYLA.OLD |date=October 18, 2012 }} at Great Circle Mapper</ref>) in the heavily loaded Electra. Their intended destination was [[Howland Island]] ({{Coord|0|48|24|N|176|36|59|W|type:isle_region:UM-84|display=inline,title}}<ref>{{cite gnis |id = 1393033 |name = Howland Island |accessdate = February 24, 2009 }}</ref>), a flat sliver of land 6,500&nbsp;ft (2,000&nbsp;m) long and 1,600&nbsp;ft (500&nbsp;m) wide, 10&nbsp;ft (3&nbsp;m) high and {{convert|2556|mi|nmi km}} away.{{refn|From the given coordinates, the great circle distance is {{convert|4124|km|mi nmi}}. See http://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/latlong.html|group=Note}}

The aircraft departed Lae with about 1100 gallons of gasoline.{{sfn|Chater|1937}} In March 1937, [[Kelly Johnson (engineer)|Kelly Johnson]] had recommended engine and altitude settings for the Electra. One of the recommended schedules was:<ref>{{cite web |url = https://tighar.org/Publications/TTracks/2001Vol_17/johnson.pdf |title = The Kelly Johnson Telegrams |accessdate = November 22, 2017 |deadurl = no |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130124152117/http://tighar.org/Publications/TTracks/2001Vol_17/johnson.pdf |archivedate = January 24, 2013 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>{{refn|Initially, Johnson recommended a more efficient flight plan that had a lower altitude for the first 6 hours. {{harvtxt|Long|Long|1999|pp=68, 72}} shows that the flight to Honolulu would overtake a Pan Am flight that left earlier. To avoid problems, Earhart would fly at 8,000 feet while the slower Pan Am flight would stay below 6,000 feet. Johnson was asked to adapt the plan for 8,000 feet. The given schedule is for the 8,000-foot altitude, but Earhart may have used the slightly more efficient first schedule or some other schedule.|group=Note}}

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Altitude !! RPM !! inches !! Cambridge{{refn|The Cambridge Instrument Co., Inc. indicator showed the fuel/air ratio for the engine. A WWII Cambridge indicator (order number AC-20911, part number 11622-1) had a range from .110 to .066. High numbers are rich mixtures; lower numbers are lean mixtures. US Patent 2,237,558.|group=Note}} !! Fuel consumption [gph] !! Hours !! fuel used [gal] !! octane{{refn|Johnson did not specify the fuel's octane rating. {{harvtxt|Chater|1937}} says the plane at Lae had 40 gallons of 100 octane with the rest being 87 octane. Lae did not have 100 octane fuel.|group=Note}}
